both enriching and complicating generic distinctions. Artists were alive to the power of the arts to reflect and shape reality, and their audience was quick to turn to the arts as performative pleasures and critical lenses through which to understand a changing world. This collection's eminent authors discuss estate design, musicalized theater, the visual spectacle of musical performance, stage machinery and set designs, the social uses of painting and singing, drama’s reflection of a transformed military infrastructure, and the arts of memory and of laughter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aJames Anderson Winn, Enlightenment studies, Enlightenment interdisciplinary studies, the Restoration period, eighteenth-century studies, eighteenth-century culture, eighteenth-century England, eighteenth-century English culture, eighteenth-century literature, eighteenth-century women artists, literary studies, literary criticism, literature, art and literature, arts in literature, music in literature, music and literature, artistic interplay, artistic exchange, intermediary.1 aBackscheider, Paula R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattigelli, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattigelli, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEubanks Winkler, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammond, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Ellen T, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Ellen T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopkins, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReverand, Ce